ions\" [ref=e1134] [cursor=pointer]:\n              - generic [ref=e1138]:\n                - img\n          - generic [ref=e1145]:\n            - link [ref=e1146] [cursor=pointer]:\n              - /url: /shorts/iltdY1Jfv2k\n            - generic [ref=e1150] [cursor=pointer]:\n              - 'link \"36 Hours of Hell: Inside the SAS Interrogation Test\" [ref=e1151]':\n                - /url: /shorts/iltdY1Jfv2k\n              - generic [ref=e1152]: 719K views\n            - button \"More actions\" [ref=e1154] [cursor=pointer]:\n              - generic [ref=e1158]:\n                - img\n          - generic [ref=e1165]:\n            - link [ref=e1166] [cursor=pointer]:\n              - /url: /shorts/QYvYQHLn8l4\n            - generic [ref=e1170] [cursor=pointer]:\n              - link \"Russian Recruits Shot at Point-Blank for Training\" [ref=e1171]:\n                - /url: /shorts/QYvYQHLn8l4\n              - generic [ref=e1172]: 195K views\n            - button \"More actions\" [ref=e1174] [cursor=pointer]:\n              - generic [ref=e1178]:\n                - img\n          - generic [ref=e1185]:\n            - link [ref=e1186] [cursor=pointer]:\n              - /url: /shorts/nY6-HqM-Fsc\n            - generic [ref=e1190] [cursor=pointer]:\n              - link \"Chinese Soldiers Play Hot Potato… with a Grenade!\" [ref=e1191]:\n                - /url: /shorts/nY6-HqM-Fsc\n              - generic [ref=e1192]: 124K views\n            - button \"More actions\" [ref=e1194] [cursor=pointer]:\n              - generic [ref=e1198]:\n                - img\n    - text: •\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"47c517a0774b4620\">>>"}],"details":{"ok":true,"format":"ai","targetId":"807C31555A855924C511E400A3AF2BF0","url":"https://www.youtube.com/@Simplehistory/shorts","refs":432,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"browser","kind":"snapshot","format":"ai","wrapped":true}},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774311880016}}
{"type":"message","id":"6e3a3cd8","parentId":"f74ed724","timestamp":"2026-03-24T00:24:54.499Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I found the Simple History Shorts. I can see many Shorts with titles and view counts. Now let me extract transcripts from some of these. Let me pick the most recent ones and also ones with good view counts. Let me select:\n\nFrom Simple History:\n1. quyuFUZmQho - \"America destroyed all of its F14 Tomcats because of Iran\" - 29K views\n2. Hg-Z1GPbDDU - \"America's F14 Tomcat deal with Iran\" - 131K views\n3. u655DqcUXbM - \"The F14 Tomcat was America's primary air superiority fighter\" - 19K views\n\n\n4. Tl0zhvkBqWE - \"How overbuilt the F14 Tomcat really was\" - 236K views\n5. SQFuqUIAy0g - \"The United States shredded all of its F-14 Tomcats\" - 137K views\n6. YYFDCxgUp6c - \"A Tank That Can Fly?!\" - 106K views\n7. yGtthJsGqeM - \"The Perfect Defense Against Invaders\" - 63K views\n\nI've got a solid collection of F-14 Tomcat content from Simple History, ranging from the Iran deal specifics to the aircraft's destruction, plus some broader military topics. Now I'll pull the transcripts for these and then work through the other channels.","thinkingSignature":"fa47ba7eb88b7ceb21ec8e95f0da2d04c69f8f9d8126f375bf47c581e74ed48a"},{"type":"text","text":"\nGot Simple History Shorts URLs. Now let me extract transcripts from the first batch of channels. I'll use the summarize tool.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vujse5bksb8f_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/quyuFUZmQho\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1","yieldMs":30000}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":12886,"output":378,"cacheRead":16095,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":29359,"cost":{"input":0.0038658,"output":0.00045359999999999997,"cacheRead":0.0009656999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0052851}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774311880026,"responseId":"06110cc849a0325f384a9fdc249b3632"}}
{"type":"message","id":"a773cc8f","parentId":"6e3a3cd8","timestamp":"2026-03-24T00:24:59.098Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_vujse5bksb8f_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Transcript:\nThe most critical component was the wing\nbox, the structure that allowed the\nwings to sweep in flight. Without it,\nthe aircraft simply could not function.\nThe wings wouldn't just stop moving.\nThey could fail entirely. In 2007, every\nwing box was destroyed. Even the ones in\nmuseums. The tooling required to\nmanufacture new ones no longer existed.\nNo blueprints and no production lines.\nThat alone should have been enough, but\nit wasn't. To remove any remaining\ndoubt, the final decision was made.\nDestroy everything.\n165 Tomcats were sent to Davis Mountain\nAir Force Base in Arizona, the Boneyard,\na place where aircraft go to sleep or to\ndie. An independent contractor was\nbrought in. Their instructions were\nclear. Don't dismantle them. Don't\npreserve them. Shred them. Massive\nindustrial machines went to work. A\nshearing claw tore the aircraft apart,\nripping away wings and fuselage. A\nshredder reduced what remained into\ntwisted fragments of aluminum. The\nmachines weighed over 100,000 lbs each,\nand the Tomcat never stood a chance.\nSome parts resisted, though. The landing\ngear, built to slam onto aircraft\ncarriers again and again, had to be cut\napart with specialized torches. A few\nnon-unique components were sold abroad.\nNothing critical, nothing that couldn't\nbe found on other aircraft. When it was\nover, one of the most iconic fighters\never built was gone. Today, only a\nhandful of F-14s exist outside museums.\nAll of them are in Iran. No one knows\nexactly how many still fly. Estimates\nrange from a few airframes to perhaps\n30. The Phoenix missiles are long gone.\nSpare parts are improvised,\ncannibalized, or fabricated in secret.\nIn 2025, footage appeared to show\nIranian F-14s destroyed in air strikes.\nBut whether they were operational or\nsimply used for parts remains unclear.\nWhat is clear is this. The Tom Cat\ndidn't die because it was obsolete. It\ndied because it was still too dangerous.\nBy shredding the fleet, the United\nStates ensured that no rival, no matter\nhow determined, could ever bring the\nF-14 back as a fighting aircraft. A\nbrutal end, but from a strategic\nstandpoint, an effective one. And\nsomewhere out there, pilots still look\nup at old footage of those wings\nsweeping back and wonder what might have\nbeen.\n\n3.9s · 2m 18s YouTube · 375 words · text via transcript/captionTracks"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":4585,"aggregated":"Transcript:\nThe most critical component was the wing\nbox, the structure that allowed the\nwings to sweep in flight. Without it,\nthe aircraft simply could not function.\nThe wings wouldn't just stop moving.\nThey could fail entirely. In 2007, every\nwing box was destroyed. Even the ones in\nmuseums. The tooling required to\nmanufacture new ones no longer existed.\nNo blueprints and no production lines.\nThat alone should have been enough, but\nit wasn't. To remove any remaining\ndoubt, the final decision was made.\nDestroy everything.\n165 Tomcats were sent to Davis Mountain\nAir Force Base in Arizona, the Boneyard,\na place where aircraft go to sleep or to\ndie. An independent contractor was\nbrought in. Their instructions were\nclear. Don't dismantle them. Don't\npreserve them. Shred them. Massive\nindustrial machines went to work. A\nshearing claw tore the aircraft apart,\nripping away wings and fuselage. A\nshredder reduced what remained into\ntwisted fragments of aluminum. The\nmachines weighed over 100,000 lbs each,\nand the Tomcat never stood a chance.\nSome parts resisted, though. The landing\ngear, built to slam onto aircraft\ncarriers again and again, had to be cut\napart with specialized torches. A few\nnon-unique components were sold abroad.\nNothing critical, nothing that couldn't\nbe found on other aircraft. When it was\nover, one of the most iconic fighters\never built was gone. Today, only a\nhandful of F-14s exist outside museums.\nAll of them are in Iran. No one knows\nexactly how many still fly. Estimates\nrange from a few airframes to perhaps\n30. The Phoenix missiles are long gone.\nSpare parts are improvised,\ncannibalized, or fabricated in secret.\nIn 2025, footage appeared to show\nIranian F-14s destroyed in air strikes.\nBut whether they were operational or\nsimply used for parts remains unclear.\nWhat is clear is this. The Tom Cat\ndidn't die because it was obsolete. It\ndied because it was still too dangerous.\nBy shredding the fleet, the United\nStates ensured that no rival, no matter\nhow determined, could ever bring the\nF-14 back as a fighting aircraft. A\nbrutal end, but from a strategic\nstandpoint, an effective one. And\nsomewhere out there, pilots still look\nup at old footage of those wings\nsweeping back and wonder what might have\nbeen.\n\n3.9s · 2m 18s YouTube · 375 words · text via transcript/captionTracks","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-yoyos"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774311899096}}
{"type":"message","id":"367820d0","parentId":"a773cc8f","timestamp":"2026-03-24T00:25:01.732Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The transcript extraction worked. Let me now get the transcript for the second Simple History Short.","thinkingSignature":"7bf9cf71eaed769c412cba85426eea0b43f90e8852bc423b068e95bfc00abde7"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_26y2zj3z4oa5_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/Hg-Z1GPbDDU\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1","yieldMs":30000}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":13832,"output":84,"cacheRead":16095,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":30011,"cost":{"input":0.0041496,"output":0.0001008,"cacheRead":0.0009656999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0052160999999999996}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774311899099,"responseId":"06110cdb01d6e27c5c9f5a96c0ca01ef"}}
{"type":"message","id":"6ff7bd16","parentId":"367820d0","timestamp":"2026-03-24T00:25:04.280Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_26y2zj3z4oa5_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Transcript:\nWhen the Tomcat was first built, the\nUnited States wasn't the only country\ninterested in it. In the 1970s, Iran,\nunder Sha Muhammad Resa Palavi, was a\nkey American ally in the Middle East.\nStrategically located, militarily\nambitious, and eager to buy the best\nequipment money could buy. The US agreed\nto sell Iran the F-14, 79 aircraft, 700\nPhoenix missiles, and enough spare parts\nto keep them flying for a decade. Then,\nin 1979,\neverything collapsed. The sha was\noverthrown. Ayatollah Kmeni took power\nand Iran's relationship with the United\nStates flipped overnight from ally to\nadversary. The original deal was\ncancelled, but not before Iran received\nall 79 Tomcats and roughly 200 Phoenix\nmissiles. And despite sanctions,\nisolation, and a lack of official\nsupport, Iran made them work. During the\nIran Iraq war in the 1980s, Iranian\nF-14s flew combat missions. Iranian\nsources claimed the Tomcat shot down\nover 160 Iraqi aircraft. That number is\nprobably exaggerated, but what isn't\nexaggerated is this. The F-14 worked. It\noutperformed and outranged the Iraqi\nMiGs, and its radar and missiles gave\nIran a decisive edge in the air. That\nfact alone haunted American planners\nbecause it meant something\nuncomfortable. The Tomcat was still\nrelevant. Fast forward to 2006. The US\nNavy retires the F-14 and suddenly a new\nfear emerges. What if parts start\nleaking out? What if wing components,\navionics or radar systems end up in\nIranian hands or Chinese hands or\nsomewhere worse? Reports began surfacing\nthat foreign buyers were exploiting gaps\nin military surplus security using shell\ncompanies, middleman, and scrap dealers.\nEven studying the aircraft without\nflying it could reveal sensitive\ninformation. So the Pentagon made a\ndecision.\n\n2.3s · 1m 58s YouTube · 282 words · text via transcript/captionTracks"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":2539,"aggregated":"Transcript:\nWhen the Tomcat was first built, the\nUnited States wasn't the only country\ninterested in it. In the 1970s, Iran,\nunder Sha Muhammad Resa Palavi, was a\nkey American ally in the Middle East.\nStrategically located, militarily\nambitious, and eager to buy the best\nequipment money could buy. The US agreed\nto sell Iran the F-14, 79 aircraft, 700\nPhoenix missiles, and enough spare parts\nto keep them flying for a decade. Then,\nin 1979,\neverything collapsed. The sha was\noverthrown. Ayatollah Kmeni took power\nand Iran's relationship with the United\nStates flipped overnight from ally to\nadversary. The original deal was\ncancelled, but not before Iran received\nall 79 Tomcats and roughly 200 Phoenix\nmissiles. And despite sanctions,\nisolation, and a lack of official\nsupport, Iran made them work. During the\nIran Iraq war in the 1980s, Iranian\nF-14s flew combat missions. Iranian\nsources claimed the Tomcat shot down\nover 160 Iraqi aircraft. That number is\nprobably exaggerated, but what isn't\nexaggerated is this. The F-14 worked. It\noutperformed and outranged the Iraqi\nMiGs, and its radar and missiles gave\nIran a decisive edge in the air. That\nfact alone haunted American planners\nbecause it meant something\nuncomfortable. The Tomcat was still\nrelevant. Fast forward to 2006. The US\nNavy retires the F-14 and suddenly a new\nfear emerges. What if parts start\nleaking out? What if wing components,\navionics or radar systems end up in\nIranian hands or Chinese hands or\nsomewhere worse? Reports began surfacing\nthat foreign buyers were exploiting gaps\nin military surplus security using shell\ncompanies, middleman, and scrap dealers.\nEven studying the aircraft without\nflying it could reveal sensitive\ninformation. So the Pentagon made a\ndecision.\n\n2.3s · 1m 58s YouTube · 282 words · text via transcript/captionTracks","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-yoyos"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774311904278}}
{"type":"message","id":"05cade85","parentId":"6ff7bd16","timestamp":"2026-03-24T00:25:09.636Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now let me get more Shorts transcripts from Simple History. Let me get 5 more.","thinkingSignature":"f6fd778cdbe33086a3544b9ae544d1be613216083bc00faa006b7082778ee1ee"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_6v1y5i1ee1px_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/Tl0zhvkBqWE\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1 && echo \"---NEXT---\" && summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/YYFDCxgUp6c\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1 && echo \"---NEXT---\" && summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/yGtthJsGqeM\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1 && echo \"---NEXT---\" && summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/-mdbo2l4riE\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1 && echo \"---NEXT---\" && summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/iltdY1Jfv2k\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1","yieldMs":120000,"timeout":150}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":14381,"output":240,"cacheRead":16095,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":30716,"cost":{"input":0.0043143,"output":0.000288,"cacheRead":0.0009656999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.005568}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774311904281,"responseId":"06110ce0f86af2ad6a8611e620766573"}}
{"type":"message","id":"1f17d585","parentId":"05cade85","timestamp":"2026-03-24T00:25:26.683Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_6v1y5i1ee1px_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Transcript:\nDuring testing, engineers discovered\nsomething a bit unsettling. The aircraft\ncould actually fly with one wing swept\nforward and the other swept back. It\nwasn't supposed to do that, but it\ncould. That alone tells you something\nabout how overbuilt the Tomcat really\nwas. Power came from two massive turboan\nengines, either Prattton Whitney or\nGeneral Electric, depending on the\nvariant, each producing well over 20,000\nlb of thrust. Together, they pushed the\nTomcat past Mach 2 at altitude. It was\nfast, heavy, and very, very expensive.\nEach aircraft cost tens of millions of\ndollars, and that was before\nmaintenance, before training, before\nspare parts. But cost wasn't the point.\nCapability was. What truly made the F-14\ndangerous wasn't its speed or its wings.\nIt was its eyes. The Tomcat's radar\ncould track two dozen targets at once,\nhundreds of miles away. At a time when\nmost fighters struggled to deal with one\nor two, the F-14 could manage an entire\nair battle by itself. And then there was\nthe missile, the A54 Phoenix. This is a\nweapon designed for one purpose, destroy\nenemy aircraft from extreme range, over\na 100 m. The Tomcat could carry six of\nthem, and if needed, fire all six at\nonce. Six missiles, six targets, one\naircraft. That combination, radar,\nmissile, and platform, was\nunprecedented. Even decades later, it\nremains rare. If things got closer, the\nTomcat still had options. Sparrow\nmissiles, side winders, and a built-in\n20mm cannon for when the fight got\npersonal. And this wasn't just a\nfighter. It was a system.\n\n3.1s · 1m 38s YouTube · 261 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nTanks evolved a lot between the two\nWorld Wars, especially their tactical\ndeployment. By the time World War II\nstarted, military strategists had been\nthinking about various methods of how\nthey could be delivered to the\nbattlefield. One idea was by dropping\nthem in from the air. The Soviets along\nwith other countries had their own\ndevelopment program for airborne tanks.\nThey conducted a couple of experiments\nfor this purpose, of which the most\ninteresting was the tank glider design.\nBehind this idea was the legendary\nSoviet airplane designer Oleg Antinoff.\nHe envisioned delivering light tanks to\nbattlefields or even behind enemy lines\nby attaching wings to them. The T60\nlight scout tank was adopted for this\npurpose. Antonoff fitted it with a\ndetachable cradle bearing [music] large\nbiplane wings made of wood and fabric\nwith a twin tail. The wings were pretty\nlarge with a wingspan of 18 m. In\nessence, this was a glider with a tank\nin the front instead of [music] a\ncockpit. Even though it was an\ninteresting concept, it proved to be\nunworkable, which became evident during\nthe trials on September 2nd, 1942 when a\nTB3 bomber towed the A40 flying tank. To\nfunction properly, the bomber had to tow\nthe glider at a speed of 100 mph or 160\nkmh.\nConsidering the weight of the T60 tank,\nthis was virtually impossible.\nNevertheless, the bomber managed to get\nthe A40 airborne, but had a lot of\ntrouble towing it. In the end, the\nbomber pilot had to release the A40.\nSurprisingly, the tank glided smoothly\ndown to Earth and landed in a field not\nfar from the airport [music] from where\nit was driven back to the base. However,\nthe project was abandoned after the\nfirst trial, primarily for the towing\nproblems. Apart from that, the concept\nhad other issues. The tank had to be\nstripped of ammunition and some fuel to\nmake it lighter. These things were\ndropped separately, which meant a delay\nin combat deployment until the crew\nlocated all their ammo and fuel. Another\nessential drawback was that by 1942, the\nT60 was already an obsolete tank with\nweak armor and an even weaker armament.\nAfter only one trial, the development of\nthe A40 was abandoned as due to the\nongoing war, the Soviets had no time to\nwaste on unfeasible projects.\n\n2.8s · 2m 15s YouTube · 391 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nThe beginning of the medieval castle.\nBefore the medieval period, also known\nas the Middle Ages, came the Romans. And\nwith the Romans came forts, one of the\noriginal bases for the medieval castle.\nOften refurbished during the medieval\nperiod, it was a time for conflict\nacross Europe and the rest of the world.\nAnd as such, creating defenses against\ninvaders became a focal point of\nmedieval monarchs ensuring their\ndynasties. with abandoned Roman\nfortresses of plenty. They were the\nlogical building ground for newer\nfortifications. From there came the\nsimple structures of the Mottton Bailey\ncastles introduced in the 9th and 10th\ncenturies. These were simple pieces of\nraised land enclosed by a wooden wall\nand were usually simplistic in structure\nand size. As time moved on, these wooden\nconstructions were replaced in favor of\nstone. And these early structures\nprovided a basis for the medieval castle\nwe most commonly think of today.\n\n3.4s · 59s YouTube · 154 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\ninaway was struck in the Torso by a\nbullet but ignoring the pain he closed\nto within 5 yards of the first Machine\nGun Nest and destroyed it With Grenades\nhe then Advanced on the second Machine\nGun Nest and destroyed that one as well\nwith more grenades and bursts from his\nThompson submachine gun he then\napproached the final Machine Gun Nest\nand was within 10 yds of the position\nwhen he grabbed another grenade and\npulled the pin as he was about to throw\na German soldier with a rifl mounted\ngrenade took aim and fired the\nprojectile hit inaway at the elbow and\nexploded all but severing his arm which\nwas now still attached by a bit of Flesh\nit was also the same arm that was about\nto throw the now armed grenade inaway\nhimself described what happened stating\nquote and even as I cocked my arm to\nthrow he fired and his rifle grenade\nsmashed into my right elbow and exploded\nI looked at my dangling arm and I saw my\ngrenade still clenched in a fist that\nsuddenly didn't belong to me anymore\n\n3.3s · 1m YouTube · 189 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nSAS 36-hour interrogation since 1984 at\nleast 20 people have died trying to get\ninto the coveted ranks of Britain's most\nelite counterterrorist unit through\nexhaustion alone but while only a\nhandful have perished because of\nphysical overexertion hundreds and\nperhaps thousands have been left\nmentally scarred by the dreaded 36-hour\nmock interrogation after being processed\nthe captives are given an overall to\nwear and then they're led into a room\nwith speakers filled with the maddening\nsound sound of white noise after this\nthey're put into various stress\npositions that make their whole body\nache before they're moved on to another\nchamber they're next subjected to\ninterrogation by a mixture of good cops\nand bad cops with the more aggressive\nallowed to get physical if so desired\nthe ones that really get into your head\nare the female interrogators placed in a\nfreezing cold holing cell and ordered to\nstrip naked even the hardest of veterans\nhave been known to completely crack as\nthey're emasculated and humiliated\n\n3.3s · 1m YouTube · 168 words · text via transcript/captionTracks"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":17027,"aggregated":"Transcript:\nDuring testing, engineers discovered\nsomething a bit unsettling. The aircraft\ncould actually fly with one wing swept\nforward and the other swept back. It\nwasn't supposed to do that, but it\ncould. That alone tells you something\nabout how overbuilt the Tomcat really\nwas. Power came from two massive turboan\nengines, either Prattton Whitney or\nGeneral Electric, depending on the\nvariant, each producing well over 20,000\nlb of thrust. Together, they pushed the\nTomcat past Mach 2 at altitude. It was\nfast, heavy, and very, very expensive.\nEach aircraft cost tens of millions of\ndollars, and that was before\nmaintenance, before training, before\nspare parts. But cost wasn't the point.\nCapability was. What truly made the F-14\ndangerous wasn't its speed or its wings.\nIt was its eyes. The Tomcat's radar\ncould track two dozen targets at once,\nhundreds of miles away. At a time when\nmost fighters struggled to deal with one\nor two, the F-14 could manage an entire\nair battle by itself. And then there was\nthe missile, the A54 Phoenix. This is a\nweapon designed for one purpose, destroy\nenemy aircraft from extreme range, over\na 100 m. The Tomcat could carry six of\nthem, and if needed, fire all six at\nonce. Six missiles, six targets, one\naircraft. That combination, radar,\nmissile, and platform, was\nunprecedented. Even decades later, it\nremains rare. If things got closer, the\nTomcat still had options. Sparrow\nmissiles, side winders, and a built-in\n20mm cannon for when the fight got\npersonal. And this wasn't just a\nfighter. It was a system.\n\n3.1s · 1m 38s YouTube · 261 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nTanks evolved a lot between the two\nWorld Wars, especially their tactical\ndeployment. By the time World War II\nstarted, military strategists had been\nthinking about various methods of how\nthey could be delivered to the\nbattlefield. One idea was by dropping\nthem in from the air. The Soviets along\nwith other countries had their own\ndevelopment program for airborne tanks.\nThey conducted a couple of experiments\nfor this purpose, of which the most\ninteresting was the tank glider design.\nBehind this idea was the legendary\nSoviet airplane designer Oleg Antinoff.\nHe envisioned delivering light tanks to\nbattlefields or even behind enemy lines\nby attaching wings to them. The T60\nlight scout tank was adopted for this\npurpose. Antonoff fitted it with a\ndetachable cradle bearing [music] large\nbiplane wings made of wood and fabric\nwith a twin tail. The wings were pretty\nlarge with a wingspan of 18 m. In\nessence, this was a glider with a tank\nin the front instead of [music] a\ncockpit. Even though it was an\ninteresting concept, it proved to be\nunworkable, which became evident during\nthe trials on September 2nd, 1942 when a\nTB3 bomber towed the A40 flying tank. To\nfunction properly, the bomber had to tow\nthe glider at a speed of 100 mph or 160\nkmh.\nConsidering the weight of the T60 tank,\nthis was virtually impossible.\nNevertheless, the bomber managed to get\nthe A40 airborne, but had a lot of\ntrouble towing it. In the end, the\nbomber pilot had to release the A40.\nSurprisingly, the tank glided smoothly\ndown to Earth and landed in a field not\nfar from the airport [music] from where\nit was driven back to the base. However,\nthe project was abandoned after the\nfirst trial, primarily for the towing\nproblems. Apart from that, the concept\nhad other issues. The tank had to be\nstripped of ammunition and some fuel to\nmake it lighter. These things were\ndropped separately, which meant a delay\nin combat deployment until the crew\nlocated all their ammo and fuel. Another\nessential drawback was that by 1942, the\nT60 was already an obsolete tank with\nweak armor and an even weaker armament.\nAfter only one trial, the development of\nthe A40 was abandoned as due to the\nongoing war, the Soviets had no time to\nwaste on unfeasible projects.\n\n2.8s · 2m 15s YouTube · 391 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nThe beginning of the medieval castle.\nBefore the medieval period, also known\nas the Middle Ages, came the Romans. And\nwith the Romans came forts, one of the\noriginal bases for the medieval castle.\nOften refurbished during the medieval\nperiod, it was a time for conflict\nacross Europe and the rest of the world.\nAnd as such, creating defenses against\ninvaders became a focal point of\nmedieval monarchs ensuring their\ndynasties. with abandoned Roman\nfortresses of plenty. They were the\nlogical building ground for newer\nfortifications. From there came the\nsimple structures of the Mottton Bailey\ncastles introduced in the 9th and 10th\ncenturies. These were simple pieces of\nraised land enclosed by a wooden wall\nand were usually simplistic in structure\nand size. As time moved on, these wooden\nconstructions were replaced in favor of\nstone. And these early structures\nprovided a basis for the medieval castle\nwe most commonly think of today.\n\n3.4s · 59s YouTube · 154 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\ninaway was struck in the Torso by a\nbullet but ignoring the pain he closed\nto within 5 yards of the first Machine\nGun Nest and destroyed it With Grenades\nhe then Advanced on the second Machine\nGun Nest and destroyed that one as well\nwith more grenades and bursts from his\nThompson submachine gun he then\napproached the final Machine Gun Nest\nand was within 10 yds of the position\nwhen he grabbed another grenade and\npulled the pin as he was about to throw\na German soldier with a rifl mounted\ngrenade took aim and fired the\nprojectile hit inaway at the elbow and\nexploded all but severing his arm which\nwas now still attached by a bit of Flesh\nit was also the same arm that was about\nto throw the now armed grenade inaway\nhimself described what happened stating\nquote and even as I cocked my arm to\nthrow he fired and his rifle grenade\nsmashed into my right elbow and exploded\nI looked at my dangling arm and I saw my\ngrenade still clenched in a fist that\nsuddenly didn't belong to me anymore\n\n3.3s · 1m YouTube · 189 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nSAS 36-hour interrogation since 1984 at\nleast 20 people have died trying to get\ninto the coveted ranks of Britain's most\nelite counterterrorist unit through\nexhaustion alone but while only a\nhandful have perished because of\nphysical overexertion hundreds and\nperhaps thousands have been left\nmentally scarred by the dreaded 36-hour\nmock interrogation after being processed\nthe captives are given an overall to\nwear and then they're led into a room\nwith speakers filled with the maddening\nsound sound of white noise after this\nthey're put into various stress\npositions that make their whole body\nache before they're moved on to another\nchamber they're next subjected to\ninterrogation by a mixture of good cops\nand bad cops with the more aggressive\nallowed to get physical if so desired\nthe ones that really get into your head\nare the female interrogators placed in a\nfreezing cold holing cell and ordered to\nstrip naked even the hardest of veterans\nhave been known to completely crack as\nthey're emasculated and humiliated\n\n3.3s · 1m YouTube · 168 words · text via transcript/captionTracks","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-yoyos"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774311926680}}
