{"type":"message","id":"5bfa4d5f","parentId":"2b0aa958","timestamp":"2026-03-24T00:27:59.804Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Pine Baron has some Shorts about American/Colonial history - this is very relevant to CozyColonials. Let me get transcripts from these and then check the remaining channels.\n\nLet me get transcripts from:\n1. rEC7-9u8gnU - \"We DON'T KNOW When the First Thanksgiving Happened\" - 632 views\n2. paaCGkCu1zA - \"How the Pilgrims Paid For Their Colony\" - 1.4K views\n3. J136uxJu9t8 - \"Pilgrims Were NOT Puritans!\" - 7.9K views\n\n\n4. qEddWylyizU - \"How 14 Men Began Massachusetts\" - 13K views\n5. _EA6Gq49L9A - \"Founding of Salem, Dorchester Company\" - 739 views\n\nThese are all great content for the CozyColonials audience.","thinkingSignature":"85f1631fd5f7b340360e83b0d077021d2973dedd0c3086fe2ba544ac08fead20"},{"type":"text","text":"The Pine Baron is very relevant to CozyColonials! Let me extract transcripts from those.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_uobz6phip6ir_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/rEC7-9u8gnU\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1 && echo \"---NEXT---\" && summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/paaCGkCu1zA\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1 && echo \"---NEXT---\" && summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/J136uxJu9t8\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1 && echo \"---NEXT---\" && summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/qEddWylyizU\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1 && echo \"---NEXT---\" && summarize \"https://youtube.com/shorts/_EA6Gq49L9A\" --youtube auto --extract-only 2>&1","yieldMs":120000,"timeout":150}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":59809,"output":429,"cacheRead":16095,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":76333,"cost":{"input":0.0179427,"output":0.0005147999999999999,"cacheRead":0.0009656999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.019423199999999998}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774312070525,"responseId":"06110d86710ee2ae3dafad2a62b9744c"}}
{"type":"message","id":"a0dbe203","parentId":"5bfa4d5f","timestamp":"2026-03-24T00:28:17.181Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_uobz6phip6ir_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Transcript:\nWe don’t know when the first Thanksgiving\nhappened! We only know about the First\nThanksgiving because one of the Pilgrims\nwrote a letter to a friend, describing a\nfeast they threw after a successful harvest. He\nmentions things like the Indians who joined the\nfeast and the hunting they did before eating,\nbut notably he does not mention when exactly\nthe feast happened. Scholars have narrowed\nit down to some time between September 29\nand November 9th of 1621, just less than a\nyear after the Pilgrims landed in America.\nSimilarly, the author never once uses the term\n“Thanksgiving” to describe the event – he never\neven uses the word “thanks”! If you want\nto know why this is and what the first\nThanksgiving was actually like, then please\nconsider watching my video on the subject.\n\n3.4s · 45s YouTube · 136 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nBefore the Pilgrims came to America they were\nimpoverished and struggling in the Netherlands.\nYet, if this is true then how could they afford\ntwo ships and their crews to bring them over to\nAmerica, food, muskets, cannons, armor, and other\nvital goods? The answer is that they didn’t,\nthey found help. At this time a revolutionary\nnew method was being used to fund colonies,\ncalled joint stock companies. If you wanted to\nstart a colony you would find investors and create\na company divided into stocks, the more money\nsomeone invested the more stocks they would get.\nWhenever the company made money it would\nbe divided among the stockholders and\nthis encouraged people to put money into the\ncompany. Using this method the Pilgrims were\nable to bring hundreds of people to America\nand send vital food to the colony when it was\nstarving. Yet there were many problems with\nthis system and ultimately the Pilgrims and\nthe investors in England ended up at odds with\neach other. If you want to find out the effects\nof this company and why it fell apart then\nconsider watching my video about the subject!\n\n3.4s · 58s YouTube · 193 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nThe Pilgrims were NOT Puritans! Puritanism began\nin England after King Henry the 8th separated\nEngland from the Catholic Church and replaced it\nwith the Church of England. This caused years of\nreligious infighting in England until under\nQueen Elizabeth the 1st the English Church\nbecame less exclusive and allowed a wide variety\nof people into it. This led many to believe that\nthe Church of England was diluted and needed\nto be reformed or purified. These people were\ncalled non-conformists but now they are\nbetter known as “Puritans”. Importantly,\nthey still wanted to be a part of the Church\nof England and did not want to leave it;\ninstead they wanted it to be remade in their\nimage. The Pilgrims were part of a group called\nthe Separatists who had given up the Church of\nEngland all together and wanted to make their\nown churches without bishops. The Puritans did\nnot like the Separatists and the Separatists\nwere even more persecuted than the Puritans\nwere. That’s why the Pilgrims left England\nin the early 1600’s. But this time they fled\nto Holland, not America. If you want to learn\nwhy they moved to America then consider watching\nthis video linked at the bottom of your screen!\n\n3.4s · 59s YouTube · 207 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nHow 14 men began Massachusetts. In 1623 a small\nfishing ship dropped off 14 Englishmen at Cape\nAnn, at the Northern tip of Massachusetts Bay.\nTheir job was to make a permanent fishing post\nwhere they could help catch and preserve fish\nand feed the seasonal groups of fishermen when\nthey arrived. They invited Roger Conant, an\nexile from Plymouth, to be their governor.\nOver the next couple years the colony did\nnot make the profits they were expecting,\nand the investors back in England who\nfunded them withdrew their support.\nConant convinced some of the men to stay in\nAmerica and soon after, they left Cape Ann\nbecause the soil was rocky and bad for farming.\nThey moved to a nearby area called Naumkeag,\nwhich had better soil, and began building a new\ntown there. They named their new settlement after\nthe Hebrew word “shalom” which means peace,\nhowever you probably know it better as Salem.\n\n2.6s · 53s YouTube · 157 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nAs far back as the 1500s long before any permanent\nEnglish settlements had been established in the\nAmerican mainland, English fishing ships would\nmake yearly trips to the shores of Newfoundland,\nMassachusetts Bay, and Cape Cod; these vessels\nwould leave England in January or early February\nand return in September or October. During\nthese trips they were required to bring far\nmore men than it took to simply man the ships.\nThey needed to bring extra men to help catch\nand prepare the fish they had caught in the\nrelatively brief season they had to work with.\nSeeing this inefficiency, a group of merchants in\nDorchester, England, came up with a workaround and\ndevised an experimental new method. Instead of\nbringing over men to do these jobs every year,\nthey would leave some behind in America to build a\nself reliant settlement. During the fishing season\nthey would already have infrastructure built\nfor preparing fish and would be able to provide\nfishing ships with food they had grown. After the\nend of the season, the fishing ships returned home\nto sell what they had captured; those who remained\nat the settlement would grow their own food and\ntrade with local Indians for goods like beaver\npelts which could also be sold back in Europe.\n\n3.6s · 53s YouTube · 214 words · text via transcript/captionTracks"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":17344,"aggregated":"Transcript:\nWe don’t know when the first Thanksgiving\nhappened! We only know about the First\nThanksgiving because one of the Pilgrims\nwrote a letter to a friend, describing a\nfeast they threw after a successful harvest. He\nmentions things like the Indians who joined the\nfeast and the hunting they did before eating,\nbut notably he does not mention when exactly\nthe feast happened. Scholars have narrowed\nit down to some time between September 29\nand November 9th of 1621, just less than a\nyear after the Pilgrims landed in America.\nSimilarly, the author never once uses the term\n“Thanksgiving” to describe the event – he never\neven uses the word “thanks”! If you want\nto know why this is and what the first\nThanksgiving was actually like, then please\nconsider watching my video on the subject.\n\n3.4s · 45s YouTube · 136 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nBefore the Pilgrims came to America they were\nimpoverished and struggling in the Netherlands.\nYet, if this is true then how could they afford\ntwo ships and their crews to bring them over to\nAmerica, food, muskets, cannons, armor, and other\nvital goods? The answer is that they didn’t,\nthey found help. At this time a revolutionary\nnew method was being used to fund colonies,\ncalled joint stock companies. If you wanted to\nstart a colony you would find investors and create\na company divided into stocks, the more money\nsomeone invested the more stocks they would get.\nWhenever the company made money it would\nbe divided among the stockholders and\nthis encouraged people to put money into the\ncompany. Using this method the Pilgrims were\nable to bring hundreds of people to America\nand send vital food to the colony when it was\nstarving. Yet there were many problems with\nthis system and ultimately the Pilgrims and\nthe investors in England ended up at odds with\neach other. If you want to find out the effects\nof this company and why it fell apart then\nconsider watching my video about the subject!\n\n3.4s · 58s YouTube · 193 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nThe Pilgrims were NOT Puritans! Puritanism began\nin England after King Henry the 8th separated\nEngland from the Catholic Church and replaced it\nwith the Church of England. This caused years of\nreligious infighting in England until under\nQueen Elizabeth the 1st the English Church\nbecame less exclusive and allowed a wide variety\nof people into it. This led many to believe that\nthe Church of England was diluted and needed\nto be reformed or purified. These people were\ncalled non-conformists but now they are\nbetter known as “Puritans”. Importantly,\nthey still wanted to be a part of the Church\nof England and did not want to leave it;\ninstead they wanted it to be remade in their\nimage. The Pilgrims were part of a group called\nthe Separatists who had given up the Church of\nEngland all together and wanted to make their\nown churches without bishops. The Puritans did\nnot like the Separatists and the Separatists\nwere even more persecuted than the Puritans\nwere. That’s why the Pilgrims left England\nin the early 1600’s. But this time they fled\nto Holland, not America. If you want to learn\nwhy they moved to America then consider watching\nthis video linked at the bottom of your screen!\n\n3.4s · 59s YouTube · 207 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nHow 14 men began Massachusetts. In 1623 a small\nfishing ship dropped off 14 Englishmen at Cape\nAnn, at the Northern tip of Massachusetts Bay.\nTheir job was to make a permanent fishing post\nwhere they could help catch and preserve fish\nand feed the seasonal groups of fishermen when\nthey arrived. They invited Roger Conant, an\nexile from Plymouth, to be their governor.\nOver the next couple years the colony did\nnot make the profits they were expecting,\nand the investors back in England who\nfunded them withdrew their support.\nConant convinced some of the men to stay in\nAmerica and soon after, they left Cape Ann\nbecause the soil was rocky and bad for farming.\nThey moved to a nearby area called Naumkeag,\nwhich had better soil, and began building a new\ntown there. They named their new settlement after\nthe Hebrew word “shalom” which means peace,\nhowever you probably know it better as Salem.\n\n2.6s · 53s YouTube · 157 words · text via transcript/captionTracks\n---NEXT---\nTranscript:\nAs far back as the 1500s long before any permanent\nEnglish settlements had been established in the\nAmerican mainland, English fishing ships would\nmake yearly trips to the shores of Newfoundland,\nMassachusetts Bay, and Cape Cod; these vessels\nwould leave England in January or early February\nand return in September or October. During\nthese trips they were required to bring far\nmore men than it took to simply man the ships.\nThey needed to bring extra men to help catch\nand prepare the fish they had caught in the\nrelatively brief season they had to work with.\nSeeing this inefficiency, a group of merchants in\nDorchester, England, came up with a workaround and\ndevised an experimental new method. Instead of\nbringing over men to do these jobs every year,\nthey would leave some behind in America to build a\nself reliant settlement. During the fishing season\nthey would already have infrastructure built\nfor preparing fish and would be able to provide\nfishing ships with food they had grown. After the\nend of the season, the fishing ships returned home\nto sell what they had captured; those who remained\nat the settlement would grow their own food and\ntrade with local Indians for goods like beaver\npelts which could also be sold back in Europe.\n\n3.6s · 53s YouTube · 214 words · text via transcript/captionTracks","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-yoyos"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774312097179}}
